The paper deals with the problem of finding planar octilinear drawings of minimum number of bends, which is a problem in computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of upper and lower bounds suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The technique inspired by the network flow formulation of Tamassia suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The study of planar graphs and their properties suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of graph theory (cs.GT). Finally, the use of bounds and optimization techniques suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of computational optimization and control (cs.SI).
